[2] Bats, canine, human New York
Date: 12 Aug 2010
Source: The Times Union [edited]
<http://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Woman-fears-rabies-shots-denied-614159.php>


A woman went eye-to-eye with a rabid bat. Now she wants a rabies
vaccine in case she caught the deadly disease. She's even willing to
pay for it herself. But state and county health officials say the
woman's bat encounter doesn't require the rabies treatment, a series
of shots that costs between USD 2000-7000.

Two weeks ago, the alleged victim peered up at a porch railing
looking for the source of a hissing sound that had so intrigued her
dogs. To her surprise, an injured one-eyed bat stared back at her.

She doesn't remember any moisture on her face -- no gob of bat spit
-- but saliva "obviously landed on me, aerosolized."

The woman called a private pest-removal company, which collected the
critter and turned it over to a public health official. A week later,
she learned the bat had been rabid and started to worry. The health
official told her to get her 2 dogs, both Brussels Griffons, to the
vet for rabies boosters in case they had been bitten. The dog's vet
suggested that she get treated, too.

The 51-year-old freelance writer spent 5 hours in Saratoga Hospital's
emergency department where, she said, even the doctor admitted that
he would want the shot. But hospital staff checked with public health
officials, and was told that according to guidelines from the U.S.
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, she would go home without
the treatment.

Human cases of rabies are rare but almost always fatal. There are
about one or 2 deaths annually in the United States, most often
caused by a bat bite, according to John Whitaker, an ecology
professor at Indiana State University and director of the
University's Center for North American Bat Research and Conservation.

Rabies is transmitted by a rabid animal's saliva getting into a
person's bloodstream. It's possible but unlikely that infected saliva
in the eye could cause rabies, said Whitaker, a mammalogist who has
studied bats for 30 years.

The New York Department of Health's website states: "Although rare,
exposure can also occur if saliva or nervous tissue from a rabid
animal gets into a scratch or other fresh wound (one that has bled
within 24 hours) or mucous membrane (eyes, nose, mouth)." Improving
the woman's odds: Bats don't spit when they hiss.

"The chances of her getting rabies in that way are probably zero,"
Whitaker said. "My suggestion is the doctors should just give her the
shots to make her feel better. ... Hey, she's going to pay the money,
let her do it."

The alleged victim contacted Bryan Cherry, a state public health
veterinarian with the Department of Health, and was told again that
she didn't need the shot. But Cherry said she could get the vaccine
with a doctor's order.

"It's up to a physician on whether they will provide the
post-exposure treatment," said Clair Pospisil, a DOH spokeswoman.
"The health department does not make that decision. We provide
advice, but we don't make medical decisions."

When public health officials determine a person has been exposed to
rabies, the state pays for the treatment. However, the woman must pay
her own way if she wants the shot. Even after talking with the state
vet, the woman said Saratoga Hospital still won't give her the shot.

[Byline: Cathleen F. Crowley]

