[3] Non Human primate, human New York
Date: 13 Aug 2010
Source: Blogs.wsj.com [edited]
<http://blogs.wsj.com/metropolis/2010/08/13/officials-seek-court-order-to-kill-lemurs/?>


1st, there was government-sanctioned geese-gassing to cull meddlesome
flocks of fowl in Brooklyn's Prospect Park. Now there could be
court-ordered lemurcide upstate.

It all began when a 7-year-old boy allegedly suffered a lemur bite at
the Ashville Game Farm in Greenwich, N.Y., on 31 Jul 2010. The
culprit is believed to be one of the 3 lemurs kept at the petting
zoo, only no one is sure which, if any, of the small primates is
guilty of the attack. All 3 lemurs have been apprehended by local officials.

The state wants to see the lemurs put to death. "We have the
authority to kill the monkeys," said a state health official, who
asked not to be named. "We don't know which one bit, so they all have to go."

At issue is not vengeance but public health. As the Post-Star
reports, the boy received rabies shots and does not show signs of the
disease so far, but health officials don't want to take any chances.
They want to test the biting lemur itself for rabies. Without knowing
which lemur to blame, all 3 will have to be tested.

But there's a catch: The only way to test an animal for rabies
involves sampling its brain tissue, a procedure that can only be done
on a dead animal. Washington County Attorney Roger Wickes said his
office began court action to seek the tests. He said his office filed
a lawsuit to give game farm owner Jeff Ash a chance to respond to the
request to euthanize the animals.

The state health official told Metropolis that the government already
has the power of life and death over the lemurs and doesn't need to
seek a judge's permission to euthanize the primates. But with legal
proceedings initiated at the county level, a state official is
expected to testify Friday [13 Aug 2010] as an expert witness in the
bid to win the court's backing.

But Jeff Ash, the owner of the petting zoo, is going to challenge the
state's push to kill. In a public statement faxed to Metropolis, Ash
disputes that any of his lemurs came into direct contact with the
7-year-old and questions why the boy's family waited more than a week
to contact local authorities.

"No one actually saw this happen," he says. At the time of the
incident, Ash claims he "observed what looked like to me a small
paper cut" on the boy. The source of the injury might have been the
lemurs' cage, he believes.

In the statement, however, Ash concedes that this is not the only
time he has faced rabies concerns. It's not even the 1st time this
summer. "In another incident a month ago, a girl was pinched by our
pet potbelly pig in the petting zoo area. The skin was not even
broken. They killed to test for rabies, which was tested negative;
the pig did not have rabies [sic].

As a result of this latest brush with government intrusion into his
petting zoo, Ash has resigned himself to close down the operation
entirely. "It hurts me more than I can put into words," he says, "but
I am tired of getting the raw end of the deal."

Ashville Game Farm will close after 7 Sep 2010.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[While this is a long article, both sides of this issue are
important, and the argument for or against the lemurs will not be
rehashed here. Perhaps the owner should be vaccinating these animals
against rabies and be able to provide documentation to that effect. - Mod.TG]

