[4] Bat, human - Minnesota
Date: 13 Aug 2010
Source: SC Times [edited]
<http://www.sctimes.com/article/20100813/NEWS01/108120061/1009>


A rabid bat was recently captured in St. Cloud, but whether it has
bitten anyone is unknown, according to the Animal Control Division of
the St. Cloud Health and Inspections Department. The department
announced Thursday [12 Aug 2010] that the bat had tested positive for
rabies and that 2 St. Cloud residents may have been exposed to the
possibly fatal disease.

"Bats are very common to the St. Cloud area. They are native to
Minnesota," said Lisa Schreifels, health director for the city of St.
Cloud. "And attics tend to be a place that -- if they can get in --
can also sometimes be used as a roosting place for them."

The bat was discovered in the shared home during the night and picked
up at the residence by animal control on 6 Aug 2010 for shipment to
the University of Minnesota for testing.

"The folks were not sure if they actually had an exposure to rabies,"
she said of the housemates who awoke to find a live bat. "In this
case, the bat was already deceased when we came to pick it up."

It was recommended to the 2 adults that they be treated for exposure
to rabies, which is a preventable viral disease of mammals most often
transmitted through the bite of a rabid animal.

"Several tests are necessary to diagnose it before death in humans.
Tests are performed on samples of saliva, serum, spinal fluid, skin
biopsies of hair follicles at the nape of the neck," she said of
testing for rabies in humans.

Gone are the days when treatment for rabies included shots to the
stomach. Rather, it is now a 4-shot series in the arm or 5-shot
series if the patient has a compromised immune system.

"We do get several calls a month regarding bats. But the last time a
bat was found to test positive for rabies was in 2001. ... A St.
Cloud resident was bitten by a bat, and that person decided to get
treatment for rabies after that," she said.

The Health and Inspections Department is advising the public to take
special care to avoid contact with bats. People who are bitten or
have contact with infectious material such as bat saliva should
attempt to make sure the bat is collected for testing.

"This is really an active time for bats because it's warm, [with] a
lot of insects, a lot of food available for them; ... but it's
accidental generally when bats go into homes. They certainly don't
want to be stuck in your home, and you certainly don't want them
there," she said.

[Byline: Frank Lee <fclee@stcloudtimes.com>]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[There are several different issues in this report, other than the
usual vaccinate your pet to protect yourself issues. It is unusual
that an animal is recommended to get vaccination, but the human is
not advised to get post exposure prophylaxis (PEP).

The difficulties surrounding petting zoos continue to plague this
niche industry. Some reasonable regulations and guidelines are perhaps needed.

Any time bats, especially rabid ones, are found in a dwelling and
exposure is not known, such as with sleeping individuals, then PEP is
needed. Surprisingly, bat bites can often be tiny and not awaken a
sleeping person. - Mod.TG]
